
  <!-- <section>
    <h1>What is HTML?</h1>
    <p><strong>H</strong>yper<strong> T</strong>ext <strong>M</strong>arkup <strong>L</strong>anguage</p>
    <p>***</p>
    <p>HTML is used for the placement or meaning of the content - header, paragraph, list versus its <em>style</em> (font, color, font size)</p>
    <p>***</p>
    <p>Text is marked with a "tag" that gives it a purpose</p>
  </section>
  <section>
      <h1>Meta Data</h1>
      <p>Meta Data is invisible to the reader but gives the browser important information about how to interpret the HTML on the page.</p>
      <pre><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;Meta Data Goes Here &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;title&gt;Brower tab title here &lt;/title&gt;
      &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;h1&gt;My First Heading&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;This is the first paragraph. All visible page content is nested inside the opening and closing body tags.&lt;/p&gt;

      &lt;/body&gt;
  &lt;/html&gt</code></pre>
    </section>

  <section>
      <section>
        <h1>Basic Tags</h1>
        <p>Paragraph:</p><pre><code>&lt;p&gt; content goes here &lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>
        <p>Headings (1-6):</p><pre><code>&lt;h1&gt; header content goes here &lt;/h1&gt;</code></pre>
        <p>Ordered lists:</p><pre><code>&lt;ol&gt; <--"ol" designates the start of an ordered list
        &lt;li&gt;list item 1 here&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;list item 2 here&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;list item 3 here&lt;/li&gt;
        the closing tag marks the end of the list: &lt;/ol&gt;</code></pre>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h1>Basic Tags</h1>
        <p>Hyperlink:</p><pre><code>&lt;a href="www.url.com"&gt; URL Name &lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>
        <p>Images:</p><pre><code>&lt;img src="location/imgname.jpg" alt="image name"&gt;</code></pre>
        <p>Image with Hyperlink:</p>
        <pre><code>&lt;a href="www.URL.com"&gt;&lt;img border="0" src="location/LL-53.jpg" width="300" height="404" alt="Alternate Name"&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>
        <p>Note: For details or more examples, start with your handout and then use <a href="http://www.w3schools.com/" target="_blank">W3Schools' tutorial</a> as a desk reference.</p>
    </section>
  </section>
  <section>
        <h1>Inline Formatting</h1>
        <p>Inline formatting specifies the <em>look</em> of the element. While it can be done in HTML, it <em>should</em> be done in CSS whenever possible because it is easier to maintain.</p>
        <br>
        <pre><code>&lt;h1 style="color:blue;"&gt; My Title Should Be Blue &lt;/h1&gt;
        </code></pre>
        <br>
        <p>becomes. . . </p>
        <br>
        <h1 style="color:blue;"> My Title Should Be Blue </h1>
  </section>
  <section>
    <section>
        <h1>Basic HTML Best Practices</h1>
        <ol>
          <li class="fragment">Close every tag you open: &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</li>
          <li class="fragment">Be case sensitive/be consistent:
            <br>
            &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;     not     &lt;h1&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;</li>
            <li class="fragment">Indent nested tags (such as when indenting ordered lists):
              <pre><code>
              &lt;ol&gt;
                &lt;li&gt;list item 1.&lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;li&gt;list item 2.&lt;/li&gt;
              &lt;/ol&gt;;</code></pre>
            </li>
          </ol>
    </section>
    <section>
          <h1>Basic HTML Best Practices</h1>
          <h5>A Couple of Final Thoughts about HTML . . .</h5>
          <br>
          <p>Don't try to mash your code together. Use enough line breaks for readability and clarity.</p>
          <p align="center">***</p>
          <p>Validate often - save your work and see how it looks in-browser as you progress.</p>
          <p align="center">***</p>
          <p align="center">Next: Debugging!</p>
    </section>
  </section>

